{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_irving_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659745/1927061201/0435.xml":{"full_text":"EASY MONEY BIG\nFACTOR IN MARKET\nWide Variations Are Evident\nin Business Outlook \u2014Gold\nHoldings Heavy.\nBY GEORGE T. HUGHES.\nDinpatch to The Star.\nXEW YORK. June 11.\u2014Seldom has\nthere been a financial or economic\nsituation more difficult to analyze than\nthe one that presents itself at the\ndose of the week. Inconsistencies\nabound in all directions.\nStocks in the main are firm, ana\nthat is saying a good deal when it is\nremembered that the general level of\nquotations is at the highest in years.\nMonev is abundant and cheap. But,\nand this is the illogical thing, bonds\nare weak. There is an enormous sup\nply of undigested new offerings, the\nweight of which is beginning to tell on\nthe market for seasoned issues.\nThere are wide variations in the\nbusiness outlook. Building construc\ntion is on the decline. The motor car\nmanufacturers are experiencing an\nunequally distributed prosperity, but\n*he rubber and tire companies are\nBuffering from competitive conditions\naccentuated by the slump In prices\nfor the commodity. Railroad car\nloadings keep up well but net income\ndoes not make so good a showing\npartly because of wage increases and\npartly because of the damage done by\nthe Mississippi flood. Bank clearings\nare up from the same time a year ago,\nbut the gain is due largely to the enor\nmous transactions in stocks.\nEasy Money Factor.\nSpeculation for the advance in the\ngtock market still rests upon the\nfoundation of easy money. As far as\nrates for call loans go the buyers\nseem to have no reason for concern.\nFor the first time since May 23. day\nto-day accommodations have been ob\ntainable this week at 4 per cent on\nthe exchange and at a concession from\nthis charge in the outside market.\nThe heavy drafts made upon the\nsupply by the investment houses that\nare carrying new bond issues show\nin the total of brokers\u2019 loans, but not\nin the call money market. The week\nly statement of the Federal Reserve\nBanks gives no sign of any check to\nthe advance in stocks on the credit\naccount. Gold holdings are larger and\nthe reserve ratio is higher.\nThat the speculative community\nrealizes the important part money is\nplaying in the current market was\ndemonstrated bv the uneasiness\n\u00aehown on Thursday, when a report\n\u00abot about that the Federal Reserve\nBank authorities were going to make\na statement after the close. The re\nport was unfounded, but for a while\nprices weakened on the idea that a\nwarning against excessive speculation\nwas coming from this source.\nRediscount Rate Cut.\nAlong the same line is the intense\nInterest taken every week in the meet\ning of the directors of the New York\nMnk. Well informed bankers can see\nso reason for a reduction in the re\niscount rate, and yet predictions that\naction to that effect will be taken are\nwidely circulated regularly the day of\nthe meeting.\nIn the railway field the most inter\nesting happening of the week was the\nannouncement by the B. O. of its\n*l*n to finance by common stock. It\nmas only four years ago that the Bal\ni\u00bbiore Ohio resumed dividends on\nthb common after the period during\nwhich payments were suspended cov\nering the after-the-war deflation. In\n1920 the stock sold as low as 27%. It\ndirt not cross par until 1926, but today\nit is selling some 20 points above par\nand is paying 6 per cent dividends and\nearning the amount twice over. More\nsignflcant still is the confidence of the\ndirectors that the market situation is\nsuch as to allow' the sale of nearly\n$58,000,000 in railroad common stock.\n'C '.e New York Central is expected\n\u00bbo make a similar offering In the near\nfuture and perhaps other railroads\nwill do the same. The incident marks\na change in the public attitud- toward\nfie carriers that only the most opti\nlistic would have dared to forecast\nVi years ago.\nBad News Ignored.\nNot the least striking fact about the\nfctock market status of the rails is the\nway in which the unfavorable develop\nments have been ignored. Denials of\nmerger applications have had Only\nEporary effect. Losses caused hy\nflood have not been reflected In\n\u2022k prices. Probably no attention\nwill be paid to the showing in this\nweek\u2019s crop report, with its decline in\nestimated production of Winter wheat\nand the unsatisfacory outlook for\neorn. It may be that the market will\nwait until these conditions have been\ntranslated into a falling off of earn\nings.\nOs course It is still early to speak\nwith confidence about the crops, and\ntft-> final result could easily be much\nbetter than now appears. The point\nis that the market for railroad stocks\nconcerns itself only with the bright\n\u2022ide of the picture.\nGLIDDEN ACTIVE.\nCLEVELAND. June 11 (^).\u2014Pre\nferred stock of the Glidden Paint and\nVarnish Co. of Cleveland was taken\nin heavy volume at around 99 on the\nlocal stock exchange today in seeming\nreflection of merger rumors. Reports\nof a consolidation with Certain-Teed\nProducts Co. and Beaverboard Cor\nporation have been current for some\ntime. The merger would form a com\nj*inv with resources upward of\n$60,000,000.\n\nMENTHANOL REDUCED.\nNEW YORK, June 11 (A*). \u2014A\nSingle cut of 17 cents a gallon\nbrought the price for purified men\nthanol down to 68 cents a gallon in\ntanks says the Oil, Paint and Drug\nReporter,* The cut, the severest ever\nmade in the price of natural men\nthanol, was forced by offering of\nt ample quantities of synthetic men\nthanol in the United States.\nMAY BEST MONTH.\nNEW YORK, June 11 UP). \u2014May\nwas the best month in the history of\nWillys Overland Co., President Willy*\ndeclared when sailing to attend the\nInternational Chamber of Commerce\nmeeting at Stockholm. Shipments\ntotaled 26,946 cars. Mr. Willys es\ntimated profits for the second quar\nter after all charges except Federal\ntaxes at 94,000.000 and estimated that\nearnings for the first half of the year\nwill exceed $6,000,000.\nNew York Stock and\nBond Averages.\nSATURDAY. JUNE 11.\nSTOCKS.\nTotal stock sales, BM\u00ab!00 shares.\nTucotj imltmlriafs avrraxed 157.86!\nnet sain. .30.\nMidi. 10!I7, 150.6): low. 141.23.\nTwenty railroads averaced 141.21 1\nnr* .'IS.\nHigh. 1927. 145.58; low. 125.58.\nBONDS.\nTotal bond sales (par value), $4,.\n854.00A.\nTen first-crude rails averaced 04.88;\nnet low, .02.\nTen secondary rails avers red 06.38:\nnet t-ain. .05.\nTen public utilities averaged 06.22;\nnet caiu. .02.\nTen industrials averaced 100.62;\nf net loss, .03.\nCombined average. 97.03: net los\u00bb.\nCombined average, month ago,\n97.78: year ago. 95.63.\nFINANCIACA\nBOND SUMMARY FOR THE WEEK\n10125 09\u00b019 101*s?l* 100 28 LlbertyS%s?932*47 lof** 100 28 100 29\n1032 101 21 10*80 102 29 Liberty Ist 4%s 1982-47.. 103 3 103 103\n101 S 100 13 101 4 100 8 Liborty 2d 414* 1927-43.. 100 15 100 3 100 14\n10117 100 25 101 21 100 23 Liberty *d 4*s 1928 100 31 100 28 100 49\n103 18 101 29 104 12 103 18 Liberty 4th 414# 1933-3*. 104 103 11\n11010 106 9 114 31 110 6 Treasury 4 Vi* 1947-62... 114 6 113 22 118 22\ntwQfl ipg? prev. week s\nHigh. Lew. High Low. FOREIGN I<\u00a3w' 1 w\n100 96 100 V7* Argentine. June 5s 99% 99% 98 99V*\n100 Vi 96% 100% 97* Argentina 6s A-1957 99 9 100\n99% 96% 98* 971* Australian Govt 98 9814 98 s 93*\n103 100 105% 10114 Austria 7s 103,4 1031 103 4 103v\n92% 81% 98 92% Belgium \u00abs 97 97\n111% 105 114 111 Belgium 7%s 1945 113 ill, i l^\n108% 105* 110% 107 H Belgium 8s 119 193 4 109%\n93% 81% 98% 93% Bordeaux 6s 97* 98 97 98\n90 88 96 89 Brazil 6%s 92 92 91V 92\n105 100% 108% 104 Brazil 8s 1941 106% 10C* 105% 106\n105% 102% 106% 104 Canada 5s 105% 106'% 105% 106%\n102% 101% 102% 101% Canada 5%s 101% 102% 101% 102\n109% 107% 109% 10614 Chile 8s 108 108% 107% 107%\n109% 107 109% 106% ChileSs 108 108% 107% 107%\n48% 23% 30* 21 Chinese Govt Ry 5s 1951 25% 26 25% 26\n100% 98% 101% 99% Copenh