99 00%\n87% 83Vi 90 86% West Shore Ist 4s 23#1. 88*\u00bb 89 88* 88*\nTHE SUNDAV STAR. WASHINGTON; D. C.. JUNE 12; 1927-PART 1.\nBUSINESS IN STEEL\nIN U. S. IS BEHER\nRail Equipment Buying Is\nFactor in Improvement\nof Market.\n\nBy the A** 'i*ted Pres*.\nnew l June 11.\u2014There was\na renewal o f buying by the railroads\nof various in the steel\nmarket late* m the week and this,\nwith the inc e eased orders for various\nproducts bv* automobile munufac\nturers, additional pipe line contracts\nand numerous! small orders for rolled\nsteel, brought* about somewhat im\nproved conditions. Prices continued\nirregular, however, with some shading\nof sheets in the Eastern ter\nritory. Pig iro a demand improved a\nlittle', with bu;*t'ng reported largely\nfor June and thtt rd-quarter shipment.\nAn easier feelfeng developed in the\ncopper market. .Producers generally\nwere reported to be holding for l-%\ncents for electrolytic delivered at Con\nnecticut Valley i ints. but it vas\nsaid that this pric was being shaded\nwithout bringing A* any buying in\nterest of important *l. Consuming le\nquirements are believed to have been\nwell covered for the present and buy\ners are evidently in< ined to wait the\nmonthly statistics ar developments\notherwise. Expert bu y ing also tapered\nofT the close of the wU ek.\nTin was relatively* quiet. Prices\nreacted somewhat, lespecially for\nfuture positions. Spotl and nearby\nsupplies continued scar e.\nLead was easier with e onsuming de\nmand not as active as ecently. The\nreaction abroad was responsi\nble for the situation here..\nZinc remained firm wi.lh producers\nnot offering freely. Ore *vas higher.\nStocks during May increased moder-\nAntimony was fractional ly lower in\ndull market. Consumers continued\nto come in only as requirements made\nit necessary.\nBaltimore Mark i ts\nBALTIMORE, June II (Si cial).\u2014\u2022\nDemand for old potatoes easedioff the\nlatter part of the week, and a hough\nreceipts continue light they are* ample\nfor the demand which is now' turning\nto new potatoes. The market closed\ntoday at 3.00 to 3.50 per 100 j\u00ab unds\nfor w r ell graded No. 1 stock and 2 iOO to\n2.50 for run of the patch and\npotatoes. Receipts of new pot*toes\nhave been very heavy this week, and\nthe market rules lower at 3.00 to \u00bb6.50\nper barrel for Virginia and Eastern\nShore stock. Season for sweet po\ntatoes and yams advancing and un 4er\nlighter receipts the market holds g eci\nerally firm at 1.25 to 1.75 bushel i\u2019pr\nsweets and 1.00 to 1.25 bushel far\nyams.\nNative and nearby garden true A\ncontinues in good demand, and values*\nhold firm at the following quotations:!\nFancy green asparagus. 2.50 to 4.00\ndozen, and 1.50 to 2.00 for culls, but 1\npartly w-hite grass will not bring over r\n1.50 to 2.50; green beans, 3.00 to 3.50; v\nper 5-peck basket, 3.75 to 4.00; for\nstringless beets and carrots, 3.00 to\n5.00 per 100; blue kale, 50 to 75 bushel:\nlettuce, 1.50 to 2.00 bushel; Spring\nonions, 1.25 to 1.50 per 100: peas. 2.25\nto 2.50 bushel for telephones, and 1.50\nto 2.00 for small; radishes, 1.50 to 3.00\nper 100; rhubarb, 2.00 and 3.00 per\n100, and spinach. 25 to 75 bushel.\nReceipts of strawberries have been\nlighter the past week, and the market\nis a shade firmer at 6 to 15 a quart,\nwith the outlook good for the coming\nweek, but it takes choice stock to\nbring top values, and all small, watery\nberries have to he sold to the packers\nat the lower values.\nClosing grain quotations: Wheat,\nNo. 2 red'Winter, spot, 1.52%; No. 2\nred Winter, garlicky, spot. 1.49%.\nCorn, domestic. No. 2. 1.02; cob corn,\n5.00 per barrel. Oats, No. 2 white\ndomestic, 61; No. 3 white domestic, 57a\n58. Rye, nearby, 1.05a1.10.\nEgg Prices Firm.:\nReceipts of native and nearby eggs\nhave been only moderate the past\nweek and all offerings showing qual\nity have met with ready sale. The\nmarket closed firm today at 23 cents\na dozen. For firsts in free cases an\nadvance of 1% cents a dozen over\nopening prices Monday. With warm\nweather prevailing, shipments in\nsmaller lots in preference to holding\neggs are advisable in order to com\nmand top values, as buyers are crit\nical as to quality at this season of\nthe year.\nLive Poultry Market.\nThe genera! live poultry market has\nan easier tone under fairly liberal\nreceipts and values show a decline on\nmost lines. Demand good for Spring\nchickens, 2 pounds and over, at 36 to\n38 a pound, and 30 to 35 for smaller,\nWhite Leghorns, however, will not\nbring over 22 to 28, and shipment of\nsmall fowl not advisable, as it only\ntends to lower the value of the better\nfowl. Market for old hens dull, and\nunder liberal receipts prices are most\nly in buyers\u2019 favor at 22 to 25 for stock\nweighing 3Va pounds and over, but\nlighter fowl and Leghorns are slow\nsale at 17 and 18. Old roosters in\nample supply at 12 to 15. Demand\nfor young ducks continues good for\nstock weighing 4 pounds and over,\nwhich meets with ready sale at 28 to\n30, but old ducks are neglected at 15\nto 20. Guinea fowl and pigeons in\ngood demand and the market holds\nsteady at 50 to 80 each, for the for\nmer, and 30 to 40 a pair for the lat\nter.\nCattle Market Firm.\nThe live cattle market rules gen\nerally firm on cattle of first quality\nwhich are In light receipt on the\nwharves and only fair at the stock\nyard. Demand good for this class of\ncattle, but all under grades move slow\nat inside prices. Spring lambs and\nchoice veal calves in light supply and\nin good demand.\nQuotations today at Light street\nwharf\u2014Beef cattle, first quality, per\npound, 9 to 10; common to medium, 5\nto 8; bulls, as to quality, 5 to 7.\nCows, choice to fancy, 6 to 7; com\nmon to fair, 3 to 5.\nOxen, as to quality, 5 to 7.\nMilk cows choice to fancy, per head.\n50.00 to 75.00; common to fair, 30.00\nto 50.00.\nCalves, veal, choice, per pound, 12;\nordinary to medium, 8 to 10; i-ough\nand common, 6 to 7; small culls, 7\nto 8.\nSheep, choice. 7; old bucks, 4 to 5;\ncommon, 2 to 3.\nLambs, Spring, choice, 16 to 16*4;\nfair to good, 14 to 15.\nHogs, straight, 9 to 10; sows, 7 to 8.\nLive pigs, 15 to 20; shoats, 10 to 12.\nWILL BUY ICE FIRMS.\nNEW YORK, June 11 C4 s ).\u2014The\nCarolina-Georgia Service Co. has\nbeen incorporated in Delaware to\nacquire business propertiee of ice\nmanufacturing concerns in 18 com\nmunities surrounding Anderson, S. C.\nCapitalization will include 7,150\nshare of $7 dividend no-par preferred\nand 60,000 shares of no-par common\nstock.\nGASOLINE HIGHER.\nNEW YORK, June 11 JP Gaso\nline prices at refinery centers showed\na slight increase for the week, the\nOil, Paint and Drug Reporter de\nclares. The average price of motor\ngasoline at four important refining\ncenters was up approximately 1-10\ncent on the gallon, but nearly 8 cents\na gallon under last, year at thto time.\n1\nMOVING TRAINS SHOWN.\nVisualized on Huge Map in Paris\nTourist Office.\nPARIS, June 11 (A*).\u2014 Scores of fast\nEuropean express train lines are\nshown in a moving network on a huge\nmap in a Paris tourist office window.\nEach train route is a slender glass\ntube with a liquid full of bubbles\nforced through it. The London-Nice,\nParis-Bucharest, Brussels-Rome and\nother crack international trains are\nvisualized. The moving liquid gives\nan Impression of speed and the web\nof lines connecting all the great cities\nconveys an idea of facility of travel\nthat excites much comment.\nWHEAT PRICE SAGS\nIN LATE DEALINGS\nCorn Also Hits Air Pocket and\nGoes Down in Week\nEnd Session.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, June 11.\u2014Wheat and\ncorn bumped against an airpocket in\ndemand from buyers late today, and\nboth cereals underwent a sudden\ndrop. Price downturns were accelerat\ned by the fact that many standing\norders to sell out and stop losses if\nnecessary at various fixed limits were\nforced into operation. Wheat harvest\ning was reported as having begun in\nKansas with weather conditions fa\nvorable.\nWheat closed heavy, to 2% net\nlower; corn, to 1% off; oats, Ik to\nI*4 down, and provisions unchanged\nto a setback of 10a12.\nCessation of buying in wheat and\ncorn came during the last hour of\nbusiness, and happened to coincide\nwith somewhat enlarged selling on\nthe part of houses with Northwestern\nand Southern connections. It then\nquickly became apparent that for at\nleast the time being the market was\nwithout any aggressive support. On\nthe ensuing collapse of prices, the\nexecution of stop-loss selling orders\nadded to the weakness, and the finish\nwas at the day\u2019s bottom level.\nA display of strength which earlier\nhad shown itself in the wheat mar\nket was ascribed to black rust news\nfrom Indiana and to a bullish con\nstruction placed on the Canadian gov\nernment crop report. Besides, Liver\npool quotations were firmer than had\nbeen looked for. According to au\nthorities here, the Canadian govern\nment figures indicate 320,000,000\nbushels wheat yield this season, as\nagainst 382,000,000 bushels harvested\nin 1926. On the other hand, Indiana\nblack rust appeared to consist only\nof some spores on the lower part of\nstalks, and not indicative of damage.\nFavorable weather in the corn\nbelt was a bearish factor today as\nto corn and oats.\nI Provisions went downward on ac\ncount of weakness of hog values and\nLot cereals as well,\nv\nr OPERATION HIGHER.\nNEW I'CIRK, June 11 \u2014lndus\ntrial plants in the United States\no i>erated in May at a rate \u00bb4 P e c nt\nu 6 der April, but 6.8 per cent higher\ntie in May, 1926, the Electrical World\nw.%1 say in its current issue. The\nrm\u00dfvlerate decline in May was largely\nseiifional in character.\n\nDAVENPORT HOSIERY.\nN fc\u2019AV YORK, June 11 \u2014Direc\ntors of Davenport Hosiery Mills\nhaver declared an Initial quarterly\ndividtend of $1.75 a share on the pre\nferred stock, payable June 1 to\nshareholders of record June 20.\n\nNow It\u2019s Explained.\nLON\u2019OON, June 11.\u2014Women are\nconstitutionally deficient in a sense of\nmechanism, in the opinion of Prof. D.\nFraser ,Harris, the scientific authot,\nand it is this lack which often makes\nwomen seem unreasoning to men.\nTHE DAILY\nHOROSCOPE\nMonday, June 13.\nGood anti evil planetary influences\ncontend tcinorrow, according to as\ntrology. which finds benefic aspects\ndominating.\nAll the sifcns appear to promise ex\npansion in lousiness interests, and this\nshould he a propitious day for pushing\nbusiness projects.\nBankers continue subject to the\nmost stimula nng influences, that push\nthem more utnd more into public al\nfa Foreign loans again will come much\ninto public dincussion, and before old\nproblems are settled, new ones are to\nbe evolved from current events, it is\nforecast.\n'Phis is read aD an unlucky for\nstarting on long voyages and for this\nreason it is well to be cautious.\nThere may be* losses to commerce\nthrough disasters or events that could\nnot be foreseen.\nThis is held to be an unfavorable\nrule under which to deal with financial\nmatters. It is a. most unlucky day\nfor contracting deibts.\nLondon astrologers are now setting\nforth the fact that-the famous Locar\nno pact was signetl when the stars\nwore most malefic in their rule, and,\nfor this reason, they foretell only dis\nappointment for all who rejoiced.\nStern foreign policies are prognosti\ncated for the United .States and tariff\nquestions are to assume new im\nportance, the seers pnophesy.\nRoad budding is subject to the best\npossible ruie of the staijs and the Sum\nmer will be a period of unprecedented\ntravel by motor cars.\nFlorida is now subject to a sway\nthat is promising and other places,\nwhere the climate is mild, also will\nprosper in the next few months.\nPersons whose birth date it is have\nthe augury at journeys that are con\nnected with inheritance or money.\nChildren boun on that day may have\nmany ups-andi-downs in life. Many\nborn under this sign are soldiers of\nfortune who meet with many interest\ning experiences in love.\n(CoD.vriarht. 1927.)\nThe New York Life Insurance Company\nOffers to Make\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nOn Improved Real Batata is the Daatrict of Columbia\nand Nearby Suburb* in Montgomery County, Md\u201e\n1 tor 3, S or 10 year term* on your\nHorn* I C Qi Offiea Buildfe,\nApartment /2 /V Business Preparty\nApply\nRandall t H. Haoner t Ss Company\nMortgagk Loam i Cobrksponoent\n1321 Connecticut Ava. Telephone Main 97C0\n'.Li' \"i\".\" 1\nSOUTHWEST WHEAT\nBEING HARVESTED\nOnly 162,000,000-Bushel\nYield Expected In Kansas,\nOklahoma and Texas.\nBy the Associated Press.\nKANSAS CITY, June 11.\u2014Hum\nming binders and reapers and clat\ntering combines are singing the songs\nof the harvest in the great South\nwest.\nFrom the broad wheat fields of\nTexas, up through Oklahoma and in\nthe wide expanses of Kansas the\ngolden grain is falling. Over all the\nland is the stir of harvest, and in\nthe fields an army reaps that the\ncountry's bread basket may be full.\nKansas, premier wheat Sta*e of\nthem all, must be content with a\nshort crop, an estimated production\nof little more than 100 million\nbushels standing ready for t* sickle.\nAdverse weather and pests cut the\ncrop to the smallest since World War\ndays.\nIn all of Kansas, Oklahoma and\nTexas the yield has been estimated\nat about 162,000,000 bushels, but lit\ntle more than Kansas fields alone\nyielded last year.\nWE FINANCE\nall clause* of income-omduein*\nnrooertv\nLarge Loans a Specially\nCurrent ml rate and commlMion\nHigbie Richardson, Inc.\n816 IMh Bt. N VV.\n1,.. v ..T.\nFIRST TRUST\nNOTES\nWe have on hand a few notes\nbearing interest at\n7%\nsecured un the best\nDistrict of Columbia\nNorthwest Property\nDenominations\nSI 00\u201452,000\nWilliam S. Phillips\nCo.\nIncorporated\n1516 K Street N.W.\nPhone Main 4600\n|g. m.=p. murphy\nCo.\nMembers New York Stock\nExchange\nSuccessor to\nJOHN L. EDWARDS\nCOMPANY\nA copy of our Fortnightly\nReview sent on request\n1416 H Street